My Favorite Graph: 
I show this <a href="images/favoritegraph.jpg">
  graph (and its associated article)</a>
  in class after discussing general graph theory terminology
  (up to connected components).
It is scary and compelling at the same time.
<p>

De Millo, Lipton, and Perlis:
  <a href="misc/socialproofs.pdf">
Social Processes and Proofs of Theorems and Programs</a>
Communications of the ACM, May 1979; Volume 22, Number 5, Pages 271-280.
<p>

<a href="misc/genius.pdf">Genius is a Thing that Happens</a>
from Jordan Ellenberg's
  <a href="http://www.amazon.com/How-Not-Be-Wrong-Mathematical/dp/1594205221/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1409154364&sr=8-1&keywords=Ellenberg">
  How Not to Be Wrong: The Power of Mathematical Thinking</a>.
Why Mathematics (and Computer Science) students should not be
  discouraged by smarter classmates.
<p>

